He appears as a gentle, tender, somewhat melancholy soul, marked more by genuineness of natural feeling than by learning or force of expression. Carni. 1. 33 is also addressed to him. The date of the Epistle cannot be precisely determined: there is no reason to suppose that it immediately followed the publication of the Satires, none os which are probably later than ΠΟ. 30, and the tone is not that which would be adopted in addressing a very young man. It may therefore be safely placed within the limits assigned to the Epistles generally, B.C. 24—20. At the same time the absence of all reference to the odes points to a date not long, isat all, aster their publication.
